natural problem: If $g(x) = x^2$ and $f(x) = 2x - 1$, what is the value of $f(g(2))$?

a_0.formal problem:
theorem
fixes x :: real and f g :: "real \<Rightarrow> real"
assumes h0 : "\<forall> x. g x = x powr 2"
and h1 : "\<forall> x. f x = 2 * x - 1"
shows  "f (g 2) = 7"
a_0.formal solution:
(* ### Problem
 If $g(x) = x^2$ and $f(x) = 2x - 1$, what is the value of $f(g(2))$? The final Answer is 7
 ### Proof
 \[ f(g(2))=f\left(2^2\right)=f(4)=2\cdot4-1=\boxed{7} \]
 *)

theorem
fixes x :: real and f g :: "real \<Rightarrow> real"

 proof- 
  show ?thesis sledgehammer
